{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518297"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:03:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:03:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.05,0.44,0.24,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41062"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5345"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25712"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2055"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9505"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44731"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41062"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to his GP with a two-month history of progressively worsening shortness of breath. He used to be able to play cricket but now he cannot walk over 100 metres without taking a break. He was diagnosed with asthma as a child and is an ex-smoker with 20 pack year. He is a retired construction worker. He does not use any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, His blood pressure is 132/84 mmHg, pulse 78/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E on room air 87% (on three separate occasions). On chest auscultation, there are bibasal fine inspiratory crackles. Finger clubbing is evident.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis pulmonary function tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFEV1/FEV: 81%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFVC (3.14-4.78L): 2.37L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFEV1 (2.23-3.82L): 1.91L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERV: 703 mL (1000-1200mL)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETLC: 3.1L (5-7L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFEV1 after salbutamol challenge (2.23-3.82L): 1.98L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPercentage difference in FEV1 after salbutamol challenge: 4%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFVC after salbutamol challenge (3.14-4.78L): 2.40L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPercentage difference in FVC after salbutamol challenge: 1%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDLCO (diffusion lung capacity for carbon monoxide)(16.30-30.43 ml/min/mmHg): 12.52 ml/min/mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is performed which shows calcified pleural plaque deposited symmetrically along the bilateral chest wall and diaphragmatic pleura.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ABG was performed which revealed the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPO2: 52 mmHg (75 mmHg- 100 mmHg)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPCO2: 50 mmHg (35 mmHg - 45 mmHg)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.38 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3: 28 (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral prednisone","Nebulised salbutamol","Home oxygen therapy","Triple therapy (azathioprine/N-acetylcysteine (NAC)/prednisone)","Oral pirfenidone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with progressive dyspnoea, hypoxia, finger clubbing, and a pattern of restrictive lung function tests on a background of presumed significant asbestos exposure. This points towards a diagnosis of asbestosis. Asbestosis is a chronic disease with progressive fibrosis of the lungs, which is irreversible and has high mortality. The management of asbestosis is limited to symptomatic treatments, as there is no treatment that can reverse or slow down disease progression (apart from lung transplant). Symptomatic treatment includes oxygen therapy, respiratory rehabilitation, preventative vaccination, and smoking cessation. However, there are emerging clinical trials that target fibroblast and growth factors that may delay disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E includes standard supplemental oxygen devices (venturi mask, high flow nasal prong etc) may be used in the setting of ILD. It can only be prescribed if PaO2 is \u0026lt;55 mmHg or oxygen saturation is lower than 88% consistently. It improves oxygenation and thereby reduces symptoms of dyspnoea. This is the most appropriate medical therapy for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPirfenidone\u003C/strong\u003E is a MAP kinase inhibitor that downregulates TGF-\u03b2 and PDGF receptors, which \u003Cbr /\u003Eresults in reduced collagen synthesis, fibroblast proliferation, and extracellular matrix accumulation in the lungs. However, the only study to date that looked at pirfenidone in asbestosis did not demonstrate any improvements in lung function test or mortality. Pirfenidone is commonly used in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisone\u003C/strong\u003E is a glucocorticoid steroid that results in immunosuppression. It may be used to treat interstitial lung disease secondary to cryptogenic organizing pneumonia, eosinophilic pneumonia, or sarcoidosis. However, its use in asbestosis is not effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriple therapy\u003C/strong\u003E used to be a strategy for various fibrotic lung diseases. However, the PANTHER trial demonstrated excess mortality compared with placebo so it is no longer used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E is a bronchodilator which relieves symptoms of bronchospasm. It is a first-line treatment for COPD and asthma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In patients with asbestosis, supportive and symptomatic measures are the most appropriate management strategies."],"references":["Miedema JR, Moor CC, Veltkamp M, Baart S, Lie NSL, Grutters JC, Wijsenbeek MS, Mostard RLM. Safety and tolerability of pirfenidone in asbestosis: a prospective multicenter study. Respir Res. 2022 May 28;23(1):139. doi: 10.1186/s12931-022-02061-2. PMID: 35643466; PMCID: PMC9148498.","Meyer KC. Diagnosis and management of interstitial lung disease. Transl Respir Med. 2014 Feb 13;2:4. doi: 10.1186/2213-0802-2-4. PMID: 25505696; PMCID: PMC4215823.","Wallis A, Spinks K. The diagnosis and management of interstitial lung diseases. BMJ. 2015 May 7;350:h2072. doi: 10.1136/bmj.h2072. PMID: 25952322.","Tunsupon P, Yampikulsakul PSevere case of asbestos-related lung diseasesCase Reports 2016;2016:bcr2015214189.","Badenes-Bonet, D., Cejudo, P., Rod\u00f3-Pin, A. et al. Impact of high-flow oxygen therapy during exercise in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis: a pilot crossover clinical trial. BMC Pulm Med 21, 355 (2021). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12890-021-01727-9"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25712"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25712"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-12-22T13:02:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-12-22T13:02:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5345"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41062"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"upda